Paragraph 4: "The NICE-SUGAR trial demonstrated this gap definitively: tight glycemic control protocols actually increased mortality, largely because static protocols caused too much hypoglycemia. The problem wasn't the goal of better glucose control. The problem was that fixed rules can't adapt to individual patient dynamics in real time. Every 1-4 hours, someone decides how much insulin to give. That decision depends on the current state (glucose level, trend, nutrition, medications) and affects future states. The consequences of each decision unfold over hours. And the penalty for getting it wrong is severe in one direction (hypoglycemia) and gradual in the other (sustained hyperglycemia). This is exactly the kind of sequential decision problem that reinforcement learning was designed for."[0m[0m
